V{{multiple issues|{{advert|date=June 2013}}\u000a{{BLP primary sources|date=April 2013}}}}\u000a{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. -->\u000a| name          =  Nayef Al-Rodhan\u000a| image         =  Picture NAR and Wiki.JPG\u000a| alt           = \u000a| caption       =  \u000a| pseudonym     = \u000a| birth_name    = \u000a| birth_date    = 1959\u000a| birth_place   = AlJouf, Saudi Arabia\u000a| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|Year|Month|Day|Year|Month|Day}} -->\u000a| death_place   = \u000a| resting_place = \u000a| occupation    = Neuroscientist, author\u000a| language      = \u000a| nationality   = Saudi\u000a| ethnicity     = \u000a| citizenship   = \u000a| education     = \u000a[[Mayo Clinic Graduate School of Medicine]]\u000a| alma_mater    = \u000a| period        = \u000a| genre         = \u000a| subject       = \u000a| movement      = \u000a| notableworks  = \u000a\u000a| spouse        = \u000a| partner       = \u000a| children      = \u000a| relatives     = \u000a| awards        = \u000a| signature     = \u000a| signature_alt = \u000a| website       = {{URL|http://www.sustainablehistory.com/}}\u000a| imagesize     = \u000a}}\u000a\u000a'''Nayef R. F. Al-Rodhan''' ({{lang-ar|\u0646\u0627\u064a\u0641 \u0627\u0644\u0631\u0648\u0636\u0627\u0646}}; born 1959) is a Saudi [[Philosophy|philosopher]], [[Neuroscience|neuroscientist]], [[Geostrategy|geostrategist]], and author. He is an Honorary Fellow of [[St. Antony\u2019s College, Oxford|St. Antony\u2019s College]] at Oxford University, Oxford, United Kingdom,<ref>[http://www.sant.ox.ac.uk/mec/fellows.html St. Antony\u2019s College, University of Oxford]</ref> Senior Fellow and Centre Director of the Geopolitics and Global Futures Programme at the [[Geneva Centre for Security Policy]], Geneva, Switzerland.\u000a\u000a==Biography==\u000aThe [[Saudi Arabia]]n Professor Nayef Al-Rodhan began his career as a [[Neurosurgery|neurosurgeon]] and [[Neuroscience|neuroscientist]]. As a medical student, he was mentored and influenced by the renowned [[neurologist]], [[John Walton, Baron Walton of Detchant|Lord John Walton of Detchant]]. He trained in [[neurosurgery]] and conducted [[neuroscience]] research at the [[Mayo Clinic]], [[Rochester, Minnesota]] in the United States. He became Chief Resident in [[neurosurgery]] and was influenced by Thoralf M. Sundt, David Piepgrass, and Patrick J Kelly at the [[Mayo Clinic]]. He obtained a Ph.D. in 1988 for his work on the ''Characterization of Opioid and Neurotensin Receptor Subtypes in the Brain with Respect to Antinociception''.<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/characterization-of-opioid-and-neurotensin-receptor-subtypes-in-the-brain-with-respect-to-antinociception/oclc/170883051&referer=brief_results Characterization of opioid and neurotensin receptor subtypes in the brain with respect to antinociception, Thesis (Ph.D.) - Pharmacology - Mayo Graduate School of Medicine, 1988]</ref>\u000a\u000aIn 1993, on a fellowship from the [[Congress of Neurological Surgeons]], he joined the department of [[neurosurgery]] at the [[Yale University School of Medicine]] as a fellow in [[epilepsy]] surgery and molecular neuroscience under the direction of Dennis Spencer.<ref>[http://epilepsy.yale.edu/education/fellowships/neurosurgery/alumni.aspx Yale Epilepsy Program]</ref>\u000a\u000aIn 1994, Nayef Al-Rodhan became a fellow at the department of [[neurosurgery]] at the [[Massachusetts General Hospital]] at [[Harvard Medical School]], where he worked on the study of [[neuropeptide]]s, [[molecular genetics]], and [[neuronal]] [[Regeneration (biology)|regeneration]]. In 1995, he was appointed to the faculty of the [[Harvard Medical School]] and while at Harvard and [[Massachusetts General Hospital]], he founded the [[neurotechnology]] program with [[Nobel Prize]] winner [[James E. Muller]]. Working with Robert Martuza, Al-Rodhan also founded the Laboratories for Cellular Neurosurgery and Neurosurgical Technology at the department of [[neurosurgery]] of Massachusetts General Hospital, Harvard Medical School.<ref>[http://cnsr.mgh.harvard.edu/info.html Harvard Medical School]</ref><ref>[http://www.cimit.org/news/neurotechnology.html Center for Integration of Medicine & Innovative Technology, Neurotechnology Program]</ref>\u000a\u000a===Neuroscience awards===\u000aNayef Al-Rodhan has received the following research awards: Sir James Spence Prize,<ref>[http://www.americanchronicle.com/articles/printFriendly/168564 American Chronicle]</ref> the Gibb Prize, the Farquhar-Murray Prize, the American Association of Neurological Surgeon Prize (twice), the Meninger Prize, the Annual Resident Prize of the Congress of Neurological Surgeons, the Young Investigator Prize of the [[American Association of Neurological Surgeons]], and the Annual Fellowship Prize of the [[Congress of Neurological Surgeons]].<ref>[http://www.gcsp.ch/About-Us/Staff/Faculty/Faculty-Members/Dr-Nayef-AL-RODHAN GCSP]</ref><ref>[http://www.pressclub.ch/menu/events/event_060710_1130.htm The Evian Group]</ref>\u000a\u000a===Neuroscience and international relations===\u000aSince 2002, Nayef Al-Rodhan has shifted his scholarly focus to the interplay between [[neuroscience]] and [[international relations]].<ref>[http://www.thenortherntimes.com.au/news/lifestyle/entertainment/books/neostatecraft-and-metageopolitics-lit-books-switzerland/1991055.aspx The Northern Times]</ref> Through several publications,<ref>[http://www.sustainablehistory.com/ Sustainable history]</ref> he has pioneered the application of neuroscience and the neuro-behavioural consequences of the [[neurochemical]] and cellular mechanisms that underpin [[emotion]]s, [[amorality]], [[Psychological egoism|egoism]]s, [[fear]], [[greed]], and [[:wikt:dominance|dominance]], into the analysis and conceptualization of trends in contemporary [[geopolitics]], [[global security]], [[national security]], [[Transculturation|transcultural]] security, and [[war]] and [[peace]].<ref>[http://www.americanchronicle.com/articles/view/194197 American Chronicle]</ref>\u000a\u000aIn 2006, Nayef Al-Rodhan joined the [[Geneva Center for Security Policy]] in Geneva, Switzerland, as a Senior Scholar in [[geostrategy]] and Director of the [[Geopolitics]] and Global Futures Programme.<ref>[http://www.gcsp.ch/About-Us/Staff/Faculty/Faculty-Members/Dr-Nayef-AL-RODHAN%20 GCSP]</ref>\u000aIn 2009, Al-Rodhan became a Senior Member of [[St. Antony\u2019s College, Oxford]] University, where he analyses, amongst other things, critical turning points in the [[Arab-Islamic]] world and their current and future regional and global geopolitical relevance.<ref>[http://www.sant.ox.ac.uk/mec/fellows.html St. Antony\u2019s College, University of Oxford]</ref>\u000aIn 2014, he became an Honorary Fellow of St. Antony's College.<ref>[http://www-old.sant.ox.ac.uk/mec/fellows.html St. Anthony's College, University of Oxford]</ref>\u000aHis current [[geostrategy]] interests include: [[Geopolitics]] of the [[Middle East]]; sustainable national and global security; geopolitics of [[outer space]] and strategic technologies; and global [[strategic]]   cascading risks.\u000aHis [[Philosophy|philosophical]] interests include:[[global justice]]; [[human dignity]] and [[international]] order; shared history of [[human]]ity and [[Transculturation|transcultural]] security and synergy; philosophy of [[sustainable]] history and the [[dignity]] of man; [[history of ideas]]; [[neurophilosophy]] of  [[human nature]] and its implications for war, peace and moral and political [[cooperation]] between [[ideologies]], states and cultures.<ref>[http://www.sustainablehistory.com/nayef-al-rodhan.html Sustainable History]</ref><ref>[http://www.eviangroup.org/events/bio.php?uid=7225%20 The Evian Group]</ref>\u000a\u000a==Namesake Prize==\u000aThe Nayef Al-Rodhan Prize for Transcultural Understanding, established by Al-Rodhan in 2013, is awarded annually by the [[British Academy]] for "outstanding scholarly contributions to transcultural understanding".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britac.ac.uk/prizes/Nayef_Al-Rodhan_Prize.cfm|title=Nayef Al-Rodhan Prize for Transcultural Understanding|publisher= British Academy|accessdate= 6 January 2015}} </ref>\u000a\u000aRecipients have been:\u000a*2015  [[Neil MacGregor]], British Museum\u000a*2014  Jonathan Jansen, University of the Free State, South Africa\u000a*2013  [[Karen Armstrong]]\u000a\u000a==References==\u000a{{reflist|30em}}\u000a\u000a==External links==\u000a{{wikiquote}}\u000a*[http://www.sustainablehistory.com Nayef Al-Rodhan's personal webpage]\u000a\u000a{{Authority control}}\u000a\u000a{{DEFAULTSORT:Rodhan, Nayef}}\u000a[[Category:Living people]]\u000a[[Category:Yale School of Medicine]]\u000a[[Category:21st-century philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Neuroscientists]]\u000a[[Category:Harvard Medical School]]\u000a[[Category:Alumni of Newcastle University]]\u000a[[Category:Neurosurgeons]]\u000a[[Category:Massachusetts General Hospital]]\u000a[[Category:International relations scholars]]\u000a[[Category:Political scientists]]\u000a[[Category:American political theorists]]\u000a[[Category:Political philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Political realists]]\u000a[[Category:Moral philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Contemporary philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Harvard Medical School faculty]]\u000a[[Category:Transhumanists]]\u000a[[Category:Geopoliticians]]\u000a[[Category:Futurologists]]\u000a[[Category:Philosophers of history]]\u000a[[Category:Bioethicists]]\u000a[[Category:Epistemologists]]\u000a[[Category:Analytic philosophers]]\u000a[[Category:Rationality theorists]]\u000a[[Category:Rationalists]]\u000a[[Category:Historians of the Middle East]]\u000a[[Category:American transhumanists]]\u000a[[Category:British transhumanists]]
